const education=[
['what-is-self-employment-tax','What Is Self-Employment Tax?','Understand the Social Security and Medicare tax commonly associated with net earnings from self-employment.','Self-employment tax is separate from federal income tax.|Net business profit is an important starting point.|W-2 wages can affect the remaining Social Security wage base.','Confusing gross receipts with net earnings|Treating the deduction for part of SE tax as a refund','A worker with $60,000 of receipts and $12,000 of supported expenses starts with $48,000 of preliminary business profit.'],
['how-self-employment-tax-is-calculated','How Self-Employment Tax Is Calculated','Follow the major steps from business profit to Social Security and Medicare portions.','Apply the Schedule SE net-earnings methodology.|Limit the Social Security portion to the remaining annual wage base.|Review Additional Medicare rules separately.','Applying the combined rate directly to gross receipts|Ignoring W-2 wages already subject to Social Security tax','A consultant enters net profit and W-2 wages in the self-employment calculator to see each intermediate step.'],
['how-to-pay-taxes-on-1099-income','How to Pay Taxes on 1099 Income','Organize withholding, estimated payments, filing, and recordkeeping for independent-work income.','Reconcile income records before estimating profit.|Keep income tax and self-employment tax distinct.|Use official payment channels and retain confirmations.','Waiting for a form before recording income|Sending an estimate without retaining proof','A freelancer reviews year-to-date profit, withholding, and prior payments before planning the remaining reserve.'],
['when-do-1099-workers-pay-taxes','When Do 1099 Workers Pay Taxes?','Understand annual filing and estimated-payment timing without treating every situation as identical.','Calendar-year estimated payments generally use four periods.|Weekends, holidays, fiscal years, and special rules can change timing.|Verify the applicable Form 1040-ES.','Assuming four periods equal four calendar quarters|Using last year’s dates without review','A contractor compares the verified 2026 planning dates with payment confirmations already retained.'],
['do-i-need-to-pay-quarterly-taxes','Do I Need to Pay Quarterly Taxes?','Learn what information is needed before evaluating estimated-payment obligations.','Expected tax, withholding, credits, and prior-year facts all matter.|Safe-harbor education is not a penalty-protection determination.|Uneven income may call for annualized-income review.','Using one income percentage as a legal conclusion|Ignoring household withholding','A worker gathers the prior return and current withholding before using the quarterly calculator as a planning comparison.'],
['how-to-save-for-quarterly-taxes','How to Save for Quarterly Taxes','Build a practical reserve process around irregular independent income.','Start with net business cash flow.|Separate tax reserves from operating cash.|Revisit the plan when income changes.','Saving from gross receipts without budgeting expenses|Treating a reserve as a filed payment','A seasonal worker reserves part of each collection and updates the annual projection after the busy season.'],
['estimated-tax-payments-explained','Estimated Tax Payments Explained','See how projected tax, withholding, credits, and installments fit together.','Estimated payments prepay projected liability.|Equal installments may not fit uneven income.|Payment records should be reconciled before filing.','Calling every payment a quarterly tax return|Assuming an estimate guarantees no balance','A sole proprietor subtracts expected withholding and credits before dividing a remaining planning amount.'],
['1099-tax-deductions','1099 Tax Deductions: A Careful Overview','Understand how supported business costs may affect business profit without assuming eligibility.','Ordinary-and-necessary analysis depends on facts.|Some costs require allocation or special treatment.|A deduction usually does not reimburse the purchase price.','Treating personal spending as business spending|Skipping capitalization review','A designer records a $1,000 mixed-use purchase and applies only the supported business portion before estimating tax effects.'],
['common-business-expenses-for-freelancers','Common Business Expenses for Freelancers','Organize recurring freelance costs into useful review categories.','Group costs consistently.|Separate reimbursements and personal use.|Retain invoices and proof of payment.','Using merchant names instead of business purpose|Combining equipment with routine supplies','A freelancer categorizes software, insurance, contract help, and office costs before reviewing Schedule C instructions.'],
['difference-between-expense-and-deduction','Expense vs. Deduction: What Is the Difference?','Separate cash spent from the amount that may affect a tax calculation.','An expense is an economic cost.|A deduction is tax treatment under applicable rules.|Timing and limitations can create differences.','Assuming every cost is currently deductible|Calling estimated tax effect a refund','A $1,200 purchase may have a smaller current tax effect and may require special timing review.'],
['how-tax-deductions-reduce-taxable-income','How Tax Deductions Reduce Taxable Income','Learn why deductions generally reduce an income measure rather than tax dollar for dollar.','Tax effect depends on the tax base and applicable rate.|Business deductions and personal deductions can operate differently.|Some deductions face limitations.','Multiplying by an unsupported rate|Subtracting the same deduction twice','A supported $2,000 business deduction reduces preliminary profit; it does not automatically create a $2,000 refund.'],
['standard-mileage-vs-actual-expenses','Standard Mileage vs. Actual Vehicle Expenses','Compare two vehicle-cost planning methods and the records each may require.','Business miles must be separated by applicable rate period.|Ordinary commuting is not automatically business travel.|Method eligibility and switching rules require review.','Using one rate across a midyear change|Including personal miles','A driver separates 2026 miles before and after July 1 and compares the total with the supported business portion of actual costs.'],
['home-office-deduction-explained','Home-Office Deduction Explained','Compare simplified and actual-expense planning while keeping eligibility separate.','Regular and exclusive use is a key eligibility issue.|Office area cannot exceed total home area.|Business-income limitations can matter.','Including shared personal space without review|Ignoring direct versus indirect costs','A consultant measures a 120-square-foot qualifying workspace inside a 1,200-square-foot home and compares methods.'],
['1099-vs-w2-taxes','1099 vs. W-2 Taxes','Compare payroll-tax mechanics, expenses, and benefits without treating classification as a preference.','Employees and contractors have different payroll-tax mechanics.|Benefits and business costs affect economic value.|Worker classification depends on facts and law.','Comparing gross amounts only|Assuming a contract label controls classification','A worker compares salary, benefits, contractor costs, and nonbillable time before reviewing classification guidance.'],
['how-much-more-should-a-contractor-charge','How Much More Should a Contractor Charge?','Build a transparent rate comparison around benefits, overhead, taxes, and billable time.','Replace benefits explicitly.|Use realistic billable utilization.|Add contingency separately from personal pay.','Dividing salary by 2,080 without adjustment|Assuming all time is billable','A contractor models 1,250 billable hours, $18,000 of overhead, and selected benefit replacement before quoting.'],
['how-to-set-a-freelance-hourly-rate','How to Set a Freelance Hourly Rate','Turn annual pay goals, overhead, benefits, and utilization into a planning rate.','Estimate available work time.|Reduce it for nonbillable activity.|Test the result against market and contract realities.','Using 100% utilization|Forgetting payment delays and scope risk','A freelancer starts with 46 working weeks and 65% utilization, then tests a contingency margin separately.'],
['how-to-track-freelance-income','How to Track Freelance Income','Create an income record that reconciles invoices, collections, fees, refunds, and forms.','Track gross activity and fees separately.|Reconcile platforms to bank deposits.|Keep sales tax collected separate where applicable.','Recording only net payouts|Assuming unpaid invoices receive automatic tax treatment','A creator reconciles invoices to platform collections, chargebacks, fees, and bank deposits each month.'],
['how-to-organize-business-expenses','How to Organize Business Expenses','Build a consistent expense workflow that supports planning and later review.','Capture date, vendor, amount, purpose, and category.|Document mixed use and reimbursements.|Review unusual or large purchases separately.','Waiting until filing season|Relying only on bank descriptions','A contractor reviews receipts monthly and flags equipment, travel, and reimbursed costs for separate treatment.'],
['what-records-should-independent-contractors-keep','What Records Should Independent Contractors Keep?','Identify income, expense, mileage, payment, and contract records that support planning.','Keep records that explain both amount and business purpose.|Retain payment confirmations.|Match forms to underlying books rather than replacing them.','Discarding records after entering a spreadsheet|Ignoring corrected forms','A consultant keeps signed scopes, invoices, deposits, receipts, mileage detail, and estimated-payment confirmations together.'],
['1099-tax-checklist','1099 Tax Checklist','Use a practical year-round checklist for income, expenses, estimates, and official verification.','Reconcile income.|Review business costs.|Update projections and payments.|Verify current forms and sources.','Starting from forms instead of complete records|Skipping prior-payment reconciliation','A freelancer completes monthly bookkeeping, quarterly projection reviews, and a year-end source check before filing.']
].map(([slug,title,desc,points,mistakes,example])=>({slug,title,desc,points:list(points),mistakes:list(mistakes),example}));

const educationDetail={
'what-is-self-employment-tax':{why:'Independent workers usually do not have an employer withholding payroll taxes from client payments, so understanding this separate Social Security and Medicare tax is essential to cash planning.',steps:'Start with gross business income.|Subtract supported business expenses to estimate net profit.|Apply the Schedule SE net-earnings method.|Calculate the Social Security portion within the remaining wage base.|Calculate Medicare and review Additional Medicare considerations separately.|Estimate federal income tax as a separate calculation.',calcs:'self-employment-tax|schedule-c-profit|1099-tax-reserve',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/taxtopics/tc554">IRS Topic 554</a>'},
'how-self-employment-tax-is-calculated':{why:'The calculation contains several stages, and applying one percentage directly to gross receipts can materially distort a planning estimate.',steps:'Add gross receipts and other business income.|Subtract supported business expenses to reach preliminary net profit.|Apply the verified net-earnings percentage.|Limit Social Security tax to the wage base remaining after applicable W-2 wages.|Calculate Medicare without the Social Security wage-base cap.|Review Additional Medicare thresholds and wages.|Calculate the income-tax deduction associated with the employer-equivalent portion; it is not a cash refund.',calcs:'self-employment-tax|schedule-c-profit|federal-income-tax',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/instructions/i1040sse">Instructions for Schedule SE</a>'},
'how-to-pay-taxes-on-1099-income':{why:'Client and platform payments may arrive without federal, state, or payroll withholding, leaving the worker responsible for records, projections, payments, and annual filing.',steps:'Record gross income from invoices, platforms, cash, and other sources.|Track supported business expenses and personal-use allocations.|Estimate self-employment tax.|Estimate federal income tax separately.|Enter state and local assumptions separately; this site supplies no state rate.|Consider estimated payments or additional household withholding.|Reconcile forms and records when filing the annual return.',calcs:'quarterly-tax|1099-tax-reserve|self-employment-tax|federal-income-tax',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/payments">IRS payment options</a>'},
'when-do-1099-workers-pay-taxes':{why:'Independent income can create both an annual filing obligation and pay-as-you-go planning during the year.',steps:'Track income during each payment period.|Review withholding available from wages or a spouse’s wages.|Project annual income and self-employment tax.|Compare the projection with current Form 1040-ES guidance.|Verify standard calendar-year dates, weekends, holidays, fiscal-year rules, and special situations.|Consider annualized-income methods when earnings are uneven.|File the annual return by the applicable verified deadline.',calcs:'quarterly-tax|1099-tax-reserve|self-employment-tax',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1040-es">IRS Form 1040-ES</a>'},
'do-i-need-to-pay-quarterly-taxes':{why:'The answer depends on projected total tax, credits, withholding, prior payments, prior-year facts, and special rules—not merely receiving a Form 1099.',steps:'Project current-year income and adjustments.|Estimate income tax and self-employment tax.|Subtract expected credits and withholding.|Include estimated payments already made.|Use prior-year tax and AGI only for an educational safe-harbor comparison.|Review Form 1040-ES and Publication 505 before acting.|Do not treat a calculator result as penalty protection.',calcs:'quarterly-tax|federal-income-tax|self-employment-tax',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1040-es">IRS Form 1040-ES</a>'},
'how-to-save-for-quarterly-taxes':{why:'A reserve process can reduce cash-flow surprises, but no single percentage fits every worker’s income, expenses, household withholding, credits, or location.',steps:'Estimate net business income rather than saving blindly from gross receipts.|Choose a separate savings account if that improves discipline.|Compare a percentage-of-payment method with a fixed monthly amount.|Increase review frequency for irregular or seasonal income.|Keep an emergency buffer distinct from the tax estimate.|Reconcile reserves with actual payments and updated projections.',calcs:'1099-tax-reserve|quarterly-tax|1099-take-home-pay',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p505">IRS Publication 505</a>'},
'estimated-tax-payments-explained':{why:'Estimated payments are part of the federal pay-as-you-go system and may cover income tax, self-employment tax, and certain other projected taxes.',steps:'Project annual taxable activity.|Estimate income tax and self-employment tax separately.|Subtract withholding and credits.|Review the standard payment periods in current Form 1040-ES.|Consider annualized-income rules for uneven earnings.|Retain confirmation numbers, dates, amounts, and tax-year designations.|Reconcile every payment before filing.',calcs:'quarterly-tax|federal-income-tax|self-employment-tax',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p505">IRS Publication 505</a>'},
'1099-tax-deductions':{why:'Supported business costs may reduce preliminary business profit, but personal spending, reimbursements, mixed use, and capital assets require different analysis.',steps:'Identify the business purpose.|Apply the ordinary-and-necessary framework to the facts.|Remove personal portions.|Subtract reimbursements or track them consistently.|Flag equipment, startup costs, inventory, and long-lived assets for capitalization or depreciation review.|Keep receipts plus evidence of business purpose.|Enter only the preliminary supported amount in a planner.',calcs:'business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit|self-employment-tax',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p535">IRS Publication 535 archive and business-expense guidance</a>'},
'common-business-expenses-for-freelancers':{why:'A consistent category system makes it easier to reconcile software, advertising, supplies, contractors, insurance, professional fees, travel, meals, vehicles, workspace, communications, education, and equipment.',steps:'Export income and spending activity.|Group recurring operating costs.|Separate contract labor and professional services.|Review travel, meals, and vehicle records for special limitations.|Allocate phone, internet, and home-office costs where supported.|Flag equipment and other long-lived property.|Review reimbursement and personal-use entries before totaling categories.',calcs:'business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit|mileage-deduction|home-office-deduction',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/instructions/i1040sc">Schedule C instructions</a>'},
'difference-between-expense-and-deduction':{why:'Cash paid is an economic expense, while tax treatment may be fully deductible, partly deductible, capitalized, reimbursed, personal, or nondeductible.',steps:'Record the full cash cost.|Identify any reimbursement.|Separate personal or mixed use.|Determine whether current deduction, capitalization, depreciation, inventory, or another rule may apply.|Enter only the preliminary current planning amount.|Estimate tax effect using applicable planning rates, not the purchase price.',calcs:'business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit|federal-income-tax',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/instructions/i1040sc">Schedule C instructions</a>'},
'how-tax-deductions-reduce-taxable-income':{why:'A deduction generally reduces an income measure; a credit generally reduces tax. Neither means every dollar spent returns as a dollar of tax savings.',steps:'Determine the supported deduction amount.|Reduce the appropriate business or taxable-income measure.|Apply a user-supported marginal federal planning rate.|Model any self-employment-tax effect only where the expense changes net earnings.|Enter state planning separately.|Subtract estimated tax effect from cash cost to see remaining out-of-pocket cost.|Treat the output as a planning estimate, not promised savings.',calcs:'business-expense-deduction|federal-income-tax|self-employment-tax',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/credits-deductions-for-individuals">IRS credits and deductions overview</a>'},
'standard-mileage-vs-actual-expenses':{why:'Vehicle records can support two different planning methods, and ordinary commuting must remain separate from potentially qualified business travel.',steps:'Record business miles with dates, destinations, and purpose.|Split miles across effective-rate periods when rates change midyear.|Add eligible business parking and tolls separately.|For actual expenses, total supported vehicle costs.|Apply a documented business-use percentage.|Compare methods without assuming eligibility.|Review switching, depreciation, ownership, and leasing rules.',calcs:'mileage-deduction|schedule-c-profit|business-expense-deduction',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p463">IRS Publication 463</a>'},
'home-office-deduction-explained':{why:'A workspace calculation is useful only after considering regular and exclusive use and principal-place-of-business concepts.',steps:'Evaluate eligibility using current guidance.|Measure office and total home area.|For the simplified method, apply the verified rate and square-foot limit.|For actual expenses, separate direct office costs from indirect home costs.|Apply the business-use percentage to supported indirect costs.|Review the business-income limitation and carryover considerations.|Compare methods without treating the larger number as automatically allowable.',calcs:'home-office-deduction|business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p587">IRS Publication 587</a>'},
'1099-vs-w2-taxes':{why:'Gross compensation alone omits payroll-tax mechanics, business expenses, benefits, paid time off, insurance, equipment, and nonbillable work.',steps:'Record proposed contractor compensation and employee salary.|Estimate employee-side payroll withholding assumptions.|Estimate contractor self-employment tax separately.|Subtract contractor business and insurance costs.|Add employer health, retirement, paid-time-off, and other benefit value.|Compare federal and state planning assumptions consistently.|Review worker classification based on facts and applicable law, not payment preference.',calcs:'1099-vs-w2|contractor-hourly-rate|self-employment-tax',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/small-businesses-self-employed/independent-contractor-self-employed-or-employee">IRS worker-classification guidance</a>'},
'how-much-more-should-a-contractor-charge':{why:'A sustainable contractor price may need to replace employer-paid benefits, cover overhead and unpaid time, reserve for taxes, and account for business risk.',steps:'Set a desired personal-pay target.|Add business overhead and insurance.|Add benefit replacement and retirement goals.|Estimate realistic working time and billable utilization.|Add user-entered tax reserves.|Add risk or contingency separately.|Compare the resulting minimum with market price, experience, demand, and contract terms.',calcs:'contractor-hourly-rate|1099-vs-w2|1099-tax-reserve',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/small-businesses-self-employed/self-employed-individuals-tax-center">IRS Self-Employed Individuals Tax Center</a>'},
'how-to-set-a-freelance-hourly-rate':{why:'Dividing a salary goal by total working hours ignores nonbillable administration, time off, overhead, benefits, taxes, and desired profit.',steps:'Choose desired annual personal pay.|Estimate working weeks and hours.|Subtract vacation, sick time, holidays, and administration.|Apply a realistic billable percentage.|Add annual business costs and benefit replacement.|Add transparent tax reserves and contingency.|Divide required revenue by billable hours.|Compare the sustainable floor with market conditions.',calcs:'contractor-hourly-rate|freelance-income|1099-tax-reserve',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/small-businesses-self-employed/self-employed-individuals-tax-center">IRS Self-Employed Individuals Tax Center</a>'},
'how-to-track-freelance-income':{why:'Net bank deposits can hide platform fees, processing fees, refunds, chargebacks, sales tax collected, and unpaid invoices.',steps:'Number and retain invoices.|Export platform and payment-processor statements.|Record cash receipts promptly.|Track gross billed and collected revenue separately.|Record refunds, chargebacks, platform fees, and processing fees.|Keep separately collected sales tax outside planning revenue where appropriate.|Reconcile invoices, platforms, and bank deposits monthly.',calcs:'freelance-income|schedule-c-profit|1099-tax-reserve',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/small-businesses-self-employed/recordkeeping">IRS recordkeeping guidance</a>'},
'how-to-organize-business-expenses':{why:'A repeatable monthly system provides better calculator inputs and makes unusual, mixed-use, reimbursed, or capital costs easier to identify.',steps:'Choose consistent expense categories.|Capture receipts and digital invoices.|Record business purpose.|Maintain mileage and workspace records separately.|Document mixed-use allocations.|Track reimbursements and avoid double counting.|Reconcile accounts monthly.|Flag equipment, inventory, and other special items for review.|Follow record-retention guidance appropriate to the underlying item and situation.',calcs:'schedule-c-profit|business-expense-deduction|mileage-deduction|home-office-deduction',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/small-businesses-self-employed/recordkeeping">IRS recordkeeping guidance</a>'},
'what-records-should-independent-contractors-keep':{why:'Complete records help reconcile income, support business purpose, confirm payments, and explain calculator inputs if forms or bank deposits differ.',steps:'Keep invoices and income ledgers.|Retain bank and payment-platform statements.|Keep receipts with business-purpose notes.|Maintain contemporaneous mileage records.|Retain home-office measurements and expense support.|Save estimated-payment confirmations.|Keep contracts and scopes of work.|Retain prior returns and relevant carryover schedules.|Use applicable record-retention rules rather than assuming one universal timeline.',calcs:'schedule-c-profit|quarterly-tax|business-expense-deduction',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/small-businesses-self-employed/how-long-should-i-keep-records">IRS record-retention guidance</a>'},
'1099-tax-checklist':{why:'A year-round checklist turns tax planning into smaller recordkeeping, reconciliation, projection, verification, and filing tasks.',steps:'During the year: record every income source, preserve contracts, and capture business-purpose support.|Monthly: reconcile invoices, accounts, platform activity, fees, refunds, and expense categories.|Quarterly: update net-income projections, tax reserves, withholding, and estimated-payment records.|Before year-end: review equipment, retirement planning, taxpayer information, and official tax-year changes.|Before filing: gather forms, reconcile them to books, verify payments, and review limitations.|After filing: save the return, payment evidence, supporting records, and unresolved carryovers.',calcs:'self-employment-tax|quarterly-tax|1099-tax-reserve|schedule-c-profit|federal-income-tax',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/small-businesses-self-employed/filing-and-paying-your-business-taxes">IRS filing and payment resources</a>'}
};
for(const detail of Object.values(educationDetail)){detail.steps=list(detail.steps);detail.calcs=list(detail.calcs)}

const deductions=[
['advertising-expenses','Advertising Expenses','paid promotion, listings, printed materials, and business website campaigns','personal promotion or mixed brand activity','Long-lived assets and sponsorship arrangements may need separate review.','A consultant records $900 of client-focused ads and excludes a personal event promotion.'],
['contract-labor','Contract Labor','payments for independent services supporting the business','services benefiting both business and personal activity','Worker classification, information reporting, and capitalization can require review.','A studio records $4,500 paid to an editor under a documented project scope.'],
['office-supplies','Office Supplies','consumable paper, ink, postage, and routine desk supplies','supplies used by the household','Equipment and inventory are not automatically routine supplies.','A tutor separates $320 of teaching supplies from a printer purchase reviewed separately.'],
['software-and-subscriptions','Software and Subscriptions','business applications, hosting, cloud tools, and professional data services','personal plans or shared subscriptions','Prepayments, bundled services, and acquired software may need special timing.','A developer allocates a shared cloud plan using documented business use.'],
['business-insurance','Business Insurance','liability, professional, property, and other business coverage','personal coverage or mixed policies','Health insurance and certain long-term policies follow separate rules.','A photographer records a separately billed equipment policy and retains the coverage statement.'],
['legal-and-professional-fees','Legal and Professional Fees','business accounting, legal, bookkeeping, and specialist services','personal return or legal work','Startup, acquisition, and capital-transaction fees may require special treatment.','An agent separates bookkeeping fees from personal estate-planning work on the same firm invoice.'],
['business-travel','Business Travel','potentially qualifying transportation, lodging, and incidental business-trip costs','personal extensions and companion travel','Business purpose, tax-home rules, and international or combined travel need review.','A consultant documents a two-day client trip and separates an added personal weekend.'],
['business-meals','Business Meals','potentially qualifying meals with documented business context','personal meals and unsupported social spending','Limitations and exceptions can change the allowed amount.','A contractor records attendees and business purpose for an $86 meal rather than assuming full treatment.'],
['vehicle-expenses','Vehicle Expenses','qualified business mileage or the supported business share of actual vehicle costs','ordinary commuting and personal driving','Method eligibility, switching, depreciation, and midyear rates require review.','A driver compares period-specific mileage with the supported business share of actual costs.'],
['home-office-expenses','Home-Office Expenses','costs associated with a workspace that may meet home-office requirements','shared family or personal space','Regular-and-exclusive-use, allocation, limitations, and depreciation may apply.','A designer measures the workspace and compares simplified and actual methods without assuming eligibility.'],
['phone-and-internet','Phone and Internet','supported business use of communications and connectivity services','personal calls, entertainment, and household use','Allocation should reflect defensible business use; device costs may need separate treatment.','A tutor documents a reasonable business share of a combined internet plan.'],
['education-and-training','Education and Training','courses, references, and training connected to an existing business','education for personal interests or a new trade','Qualification rules and travel components require separate review.','A trainer retains the course outline and explains how continuing education relates to current services.'],
['equipment-and-tools','Equipment and Tools','computers, cameras, machinery, hand tools, and other business property','personal use of devices or tools','Capitalization, depreciation, expensing elections, listed property, and disposition rules may apply.','A landscaper flags a major mower purchase instead of treating it as routine supplies.'],
['retirement-contributions','Retirement Contributions','eligible contributions to retirement arrangements available to self-employed people','personal savings outside a qualified arrangement','Plan type, limits, deadlines, compensation definitions, and employee coverage matter.','A consultant enters a planning contribution separately and verifies it against the plan provider and current IRS guidance.'],
['self-employed-health-insurance','Self-Employed Health Insurance','potentially eligible health, dental, and qualifying long-term-care premiums','premiums not meeting the applicable requirements','Eligibility, earned-income limits, employer-plan access, and deduction placement require review.','A freelancer keeps premium statements and tests eligibility separately from Schedule C operating expenses.']
].map(([slug,title,covers,mixed,special,example])=>({slug,title,covers,mixed,special,example}));
const deductionDetail={
'advertising-expenses':{examples:'online search and social advertising|print advertisements|business sponsorships|promotional materials|website advertising campaigns',mixed:'Personal reputation-building, political activity, charitable gifts, and promotion serving both personal and business purposes need separate factual review.',reimburse:'Client-funded campaigns and reimbursed promotional costs should be tracked separately so the same economic cost is not counted twice.',records:'Keep invoices, insertion orders, sponsorship contracts, creative approvals, dates, payment evidence, and campaign reports.',special:'Prepaid campaigns may span tax years. Website development, acquired branding assets, and other long-lived intangible costs may require capitalization or different timing.',profs:'consultants|real-estate-agents|online-sellers|content-creators',edu:'1099-tax-deductions|how-to-organize-business-expenses|difference-between-expense-and-deduction',calcs:'business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit|freelance-income',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/instructions/i1040sc">Schedule C instructions</a>'},
'contract-labor':{examples:'payments to project freelancers|subcontracted production work|outside technical services|temporary independent project help',mixed:'Payments for household help, personal projects, or owner services are not automatically contract-labor business expenses.',reimburse:'Separate contractor fees from reimbursed travel, materials, or other pass-through costs and apply a consistent documented policy.',records:'Keep signed scopes, invoices, payment records, taxpayer-information documents, deliverables, and classification analysis.',special:'Employee wages belong in a different category. Worker classification depends on the full relationship, not the contract label. Information returns and international payees can involve additional requirements that need official or professional review.',profs:'consultants|photographers|web-developers|content-creators',edu:'1099-tax-deductions|what-records-should-independent-contractors-keep|how-to-organize-business-expenses',calcs:'business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/small-businesses-self-employed/independent-contractor-self-employed-or-employee">IRS worker-classification guidance</a>'},
'office-supplies':{examples:'paper and stationery|printer ink and toner|postage and shipping supplies|folders and labels|small administrative consumables',mixed:'Household stationery, school supplies, and shared consumables require a supported business-use allocation or exclusion.',reimburse:'Supplies purchased for a client and reimbursed separately should be recorded consistently with the related reimbursement.',records:'Keep itemized receipts, dates, purpose notes, project references, reimbursement details, and an inventory record where goods are held for sale.',special:'Computers, printers, furniture, durable equipment, and items held for sale may not be routine supplies and can require capitalization, depreciation, or inventory treatment.',profs:'tutors|graphic-designers|cleaning-businesses|online-sellers',edu:'common-business-expenses-for-freelancers|difference-between-expense-and-deduction|how-to-organize-business-expenses',calcs:'business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/instructions/i1040sc">Schedule C instructions</a>'},
'software-and-subscriptions':{examples:'business software|cloud storage|design and development tools|accounting applications|project-management services|professional data subscriptions',mixed:'Shared family plans, entertainment features, and personal projects may require allocation based on a reasonable documented method.',reimburse:'Client-paid licenses and reimbursed subscriptions should not be counted again as the worker’s unsupported out-of-pocket cost.',records:'Keep vendor invoices, plan terms, service periods, user lists, payment evidence, cancellation records, and business-use support.',special:'Annual and prepaid plans can cross tax years. Acquired software, website development, licenses, and other intangible costs may require capitalization, amortization, or other timing review.',profs:'web-developers|software-developers|graphic-designers|content-creators|consultants',edu:'common-business-expenses-for-freelancers|difference-between-expense-and-deduction|how-tax-deductions-reduce-taxable-income',calcs:'business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit|freelance-income',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/instructions/i1040sc">Schedule C instructions</a>'},
'business-insurance':{examples:'general liability coverage|professional liability coverage|commercial vehicle coverage|equipment and inland-marine coverage|cyber coverage|business property insurance',mixed:'Personal auto, renters, homeowners, disability, and other personal policies are not automatically business insurance; mixed policies require careful allocation.',reimburse:'Premium reimbursements, claim proceeds, refunds, and audit adjustments should be retained and reviewed separately.',records:'Keep policy declarations, invoices, coverage periods, insured-property schedules, payment records, refunds, and claim documents.',special:'Self-employed health insurance follows separate adjustment rules. Life-insurance arrangements involving an owner or beneficiary can have special limitations and should not be assumed deductible.',profs:'consultants|photographers|personal-trainers|cleaning-businesses',edu:'1099-tax-deductions|difference-between-expense-and-deduction|how-to-organize-business-expenses',calcs:'business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/instructions/i1040sc">Schedule C instructions</a>'},
'legal-and-professional-fees':{examples:'business attorneys|accountants and bookkeepers|business-related tax preparation|specialist consultants|licensing assistance',mixed:'Personal return preparation, estate planning, divorce, and other personal legal work should be separated from supported business services.',reimburse:'Client-reimbursed specialist costs and retainers later refunded should be tracked separately.',records:'Keep engagement letters, detailed invoices, work descriptions, allocation schedules, payment evidence, and deliverables.',special:'Business formation, acquisition, financing, defense of title, and other capital-transaction fees may need capitalization or special treatment instead of a current operating deduction.',profs:'real-estate-agents|consultants|online-sellers|independent-contractors',edu:'1099-tax-deductions|difference-between-expense-and-deduction|what-records-should-independent-contractors-keep',calcs:'business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/instructions/i1040sc">Schedule C instructions</a>'},
'business-travel':{examples:'business transportation|lodging|baggage charges|local transportation|other supported trip costs',mixed:'Personal vacation days, companion travel, sightseeing, and other personal portions should be separated. A business purpose does not automatically convert an entire trip.',reimburse:'Track accountable reimbursements, client-paid lodging, credits, refunds, and loyalty redemptions separately from out-of-pocket costs.',records:'Keep dates, destination, business purpose, itinerary, attendees, receipts, lodging folios, transportation records, and allocation notes.',special:'International travel, combined business and personal trips, conventions, companion travel, and temporary versus indefinite work locations can require detailed rules and professional review.',profs:'consultants|real-estate-agents|photographers|content-creators',edu:'1099-tax-deductions|how-to-organize-business-expenses|what-records-should-independent-contractors-keep',calcs:'business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p463">IRS Publication 463</a>'},
'business-meals':{examples:'potentially qualifying client meals|meals during supported business travel|meals connected with a documented business discussion',mixed:'Personal meals, family meals, and the personal portion of combined events should be excluded. Entertainment and meals can follow different treatment.',reimburse:'Record who reimbursed the meal, the amount, and whether it was billed to a client so the cost is not counted twice.',records:'Keep date, location, amount, attendees, business relationship, business purpose, itemized receipt, and reimbursement details.',special:'Applicable deductibility percentages and exceptions can change and must be verified from current official guidance; this page intentionally hard-codes no percentage.',profs:'consultants|real-estate-agents|photographers|content-creators',edu:'1099-tax-deductions|difference-between-expense-and-deduction|how-to-organize-business-expenses',calcs:'business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p463">IRS Publication 463</a>'},
'vehicle-expenses':{examples:'business miles under the standard method|fuel and repairs under an actual-cost comparison|vehicle insurance and registration|depreciation planning|business parking and tolls',mixed:'Ordinary commuting and personal driving are not automatically business travel. Actual costs require a supported business-use percentage.',reimburse:'Mileage allowances, client reimbursements, insurance proceeds, and rebates should be recorded separately.',records:'Maintain contemporaneous mileage dates, destinations, purpose, odometer readings, receipts, ownership or lease documents, and reimbursement records.',special:'Method eligibility and switching rules, depreciation, listed-property considerations, leases, vehicle dispositions, and midyear mileage-rate changes require current review.',profs:'rideshare-drivers|delivery-drivers|real-estate-agents|landscapers|cleaning-businesses',edu:'standard-mileage-vs-actual-expenses|1099-tax-deductions|what-records-should-independent-contractors-keep',calcs:'mileage-deduction|business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p463">IRS Publication 463</a>'},
'home-office-expenses':{examples:'direct workspace repairs|supported portions of utilities and housing costs|workspace insurance allocations|simplified-method planning amounts',mixed:'Shared personal spaces generally raise regular-and-exclusive-use concerns. Business-use percentage must be based on supported measurements.',reimburse:'Employer, client, or business reimbursements and shared household payments should be tracked separately.',records:'Keep measurements, floor plans, photographs where useful, direct-expense receipts, indirect home-cost records, dates of use, and prior depreciation information.',special:'Principal-place-of-business rules, regular and exclusive use, simplified versus actual methods, direct and indirect costs, business-income limitations, depreciation, sale effects, and daycare exceptions require current guidance.',profs:'consultants|graphic-designers|web-developers|personal-trainers',edu:'home-office-deduction-explained|1099-tax-deductions|how-to-organize-business-expenses',calcs:'home-office-deduction|business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p587">IRS Publication 587</a>'},
'phone-and-internet':{examples:'a separate business phone line|additional line charges|supported business use of internet service|business communications applications',mixed:'Personal calls, streaming, household internet use, and shared devices require a reasonable documented business-use method.',reimburse:'Client or employer reimbursements and bundled service credits should be separated from remaining out-of-pocket cost.',records:'Keep monthly bills, line details, service agreements, business-use calculations, calendars or logs supporting methodology, and reimbursement records.',special:'Device purchases are different from service charges and may require equipment, capitalization, or depreciation review.',profs:'gig-workers|tutors|consultants|content-creators',edu:'common-business-expenses-for-freelancers|difference-between-expense-and-deduction|how-to-organize-business-expenses',calcs:'business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/instructions/i1040sc">Schedule C instructions</a>'},
'education-and-training':{examples:'courses and workshops|professional conferences|books and publications|continuing education|certification maintenance',mixed:'Personal enrichment and education unrelated to the current business should be separated.',reimburse:'Scholarships, employer or client reimbursements, conference refunds, and bundled travel credits should be tracked separately.',records:'Keep course descriptions, agendas, proof of attendance, receipts, credentials, travel records, and notes connecting training to current business skills.',special:'Education that qualifies someone for a new trade or business may receive different treatment. Travel, lodging, meals, degrees, and long-term programs require separate review.',profs:'software-developers|tutors|personal-trainers|consultants',edu:'1099-tax-deductions|difference-between-expense-and-deduction|what-records-should-independent-contractors-keep',calcs:'business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/taxtopics/tc513">IRS Topic 513</a>'},
'equipment-and-tools':{examples:'computers and mobile devices|cameras|machinery|hand tools|office furniture|specialized business equipment',mixed:'Personal use of computers, cameras, phones, tools, furniture, and machinery must be excluded or allocated using supported records.',reimburse:'Client-funded tools, trade-ins, rebates, insurance recoveries, and employee reimbursements should be recorded separately.',records:'Keep purchase invoices, serial numbers, placed-in-service dates, business-use logs, repair records, depreciation schedules, financing records, and sale documents.',special:'Equipment is not automatically a supply. Capitalization, depreciation, immediate-expensing elections, listed property, repairs versus improvements, and sale or disposal consequences require review. This site does not calculate depreciation.',profs:'photographers|landscapers|handymen|personal-trainers|content-creators',edu:'difference-between-expense-and-deduction|how-tax-deductions-reduce-taxable-income|how-to-organize-business-expenses',calcs:'business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p946">IRS Publication 946</a>'},
'retirement-contributions':{examples:'planning for SEP arrangements|one-participant 401(k) contributions|SIMPLE arrangements|other eligible self-employed retirement plans',mixed:'Personal savings outside an eligible arrangement and contributions exceeding supported plan amounts should not be treated as business operating costs.',reimburse:'Employer contributions, employee deferrals, corrections, refunds, and plan expenses should be identified separately.',records:'Keep plan documents, adoption agreements, provider statements, compensation calculations, contribution confirmations, filings, and correction records.',special:'Plan types have different employee and employer concepts, earned-income calculations, annual limits, setup and contribution deadlines, employee-coverage rules, and administration. Limits change by tax year and are not hard-coded here.',profs:'consultants|software-developers|real-estate-agents|independent-contractors',edu:'how-tax-deductions-reduce-taxable-income|how-to-save-for-quarterly-taxes|what-records-should-independent-contractors-keep',calcs:'1099-take-home-pay|federal-income-tax|contractor-hourly-rate|business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/retirement-plans/retirement-plans-for-small-entities-and-self-employed">IRS retirement plans for self-employed people</a>'},
'self-employed-health-insurance':{examples:'potentially eligible medical premiums|dental and vision premiums|certain qualified long-term-care premiums for eligible people',mixed:'Personal coverage can potentially produce an income-tax adjustment only when all requirements are met; it is not automatically a Schedule C operating expense.',reimburse:'Premium tax credits, marketplace adjustments, employer subsidies, reimbursements, and refunds should be retained and reviewed together.',records:'Keep policy documents, monthly premium statements, proof of payment, coverage dates, covered-person details, marketplace forms, subsidy records, and net-profit calculations.',special:'Eligibility depends on facts, employer-subsidized coverage can limit treatment, net-profit limitations may apply, and marketplace premium-tax-credit interactions can require Form 7206 or professional review.',profs:'freelancers|consultants|real-estate-agents|personal-trainers',edu:'how-tax-deductions-reduce-taxable-income|1099-tax-deductions|what-records-should-independent-contractors-keep',calcs:'1099-take-home-pay|federal-income-tax|business-expense-deduction|schedule-c-profit',source:'<a href="https://www.irs.gov/instructions/i7206">Instructions for Form 7206</a>'}
};
